This is a great little code editor with all the basic functionality you'd expect in a full IDE. A scrolling tab bar at the top allows you to quickly switch between files. You can't move the tabs around. It remembers the files you had open when you open the app, but there is no project support (i.e. sets of files to open at once). It consistently catches files that were modified outside the editor and asks you what to do. The syntax highlighting is helpful, but slows down to a crawl on moderately-sized files. Turn it off and the editor is very responsive. There is no code completion. Full support for external keyboards and keyboard shortcuts, such as shift/tab-indent of selected text. The display and keyboard shortcuts are highly configurable. You can mimic shortcuts from other IDE's. No split screen view, but it supports the Samsung multi-window feature. A couple minor annoying bugs besides the large file issue: It seems to have trouble remembering the scroll position when switching tabs, and the cursor position will jump elsewhere when a Bluetooth keyboard connects or disconnects. [edit] Downgrading rating: DOES NOT SUPPORT EXTERNAL SD on Lollipop+

However, as my project files become large, DroidEdit Pro has started to get slow as well in terms of responsiveness. I believe this could be because of syntax highlighting engine that was used before, but I'm not sure entirely so I could very well be wrong. I still love using DroidEdit Pro and would love to remain as my only editor, but because of the lags, I've started looking at other editor apps to support DroidEdit Pro on larger files. I still think it deserves 5 stars though, it's an excellent app, just not on large files now.

When looking at a large file, the app appears to hang, but actually it is just reading the large file. The OS will pop up a dialog, and you can tap on "Wait" if you want to give the program more time to finish reading, or searching. Certain other text viewers do not have this waiting problem, so perhaps the DroidEdit will someday be able to speed up and avoid the wait. I still say this is an excellent program, and the pro version is such a bargain.

I had a strange experience with this app. On first install (paid version) I couldn't get FTP working. It started working after I added a 2nd site, maybe connectivity blip, more likely strange bug in FTP settings.   The settings screens and the overall app feel is great. Simple elegant design, easy to understand, good keyboard & virtual keyboard support (Hacker's Keyboard v good).  My main issue is performance. I'm running on a Galaxy Tab 2, so with a reasonable system spec. There's a noticeable multiple-second lag while line numbering and syntax highlighting calculates, on moderate files (ex 3395 line, 60Kb CSS file). In comparison, on a 4 year old basic Dell laptop, Notepad++ opens the file *instantly* with syntax highlighted.  Text editors don't have anything too fancy to do, and a basic requirement is not to have to wait more than a second with a text file that's <100Kb in size. Bearing in mind that when switching to the browser to test CSS, then switching back to the app means the lag happens again (line numbers are gone, syntax highlighting is gone), and this every time you switch back to the app. That's why no 5 stars. For simple files it's perfect.

I have tried probably all the editors here on the play store and this is by far the best one.  Pros: SFTP, custom themes, work with multiple documents, support for many languages, keyboard shortcuts and lots of options.   Cons: not a real IDE, not ideal for real development work (but great for what it is), somewhat limited in its connectivity options.   Critiques: color coding is slow, text is all white as you scroll document and only shows coloring once scrolling stops, also scrolling is relatively laggy which on my quad core device rendering text color should not be at all laggy, this is why I rated 4 instead of 5.  Conclusion: this is a great app for developers looking to make quick edits in a mobile environment, sadly enough traditional desktops and workstations still provide a better experience but for making fixes in a pinch on your mobile device this is probably the absolute best app for android right now.
